{{good article}} {{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants= Bank Markazi v. Peterson |ArgueDate=January 13 |ArgueYear=2016 |DecideDate=April 20 |DecideYear=2016 |FullName=Bank Markazi, {{aka}} the Central Bank of Iran, Petitioner v. Deborah Peterson, et al. |USVol=578 |USPage=___ |ParallelCitations=136 S. Ct. 1310; 194 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 463; 2016 [[U.S. LEXIS]] 2799 |Docket=14-770 |OralArgument=https://www.oyez.org/cases/2015/14-770 |OpinionAnnouncement=https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/15pdf/14-770_9o6b.pdf |Prior= ''Peterson, et al. v. Islamic Republic of Iran, Bank Markazi {{aka}} Central Bank of Iran, Banca UBAE, Citibank, and Clearstream Banking'', No. 10&nbsp;Civ.&nbsp;4518 ([[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|S.D. NY]], July 9, 2013);<ref name="Bank Markazi cert petition">{{Cite report |authors=Jeffery K. Lamken, Robert K. Kry, Justin M. Ellis (MoloLamken LLP); David M. Lindsey, Andreas A. Frischknect (Chaffetz Lindsey LLP)|date=2015 |title=In the Supreme Court of the United States: Bank Markazi, the Central Bank of Iran, Petitioner, v. Deborah D. Peterson, et al., Respondents; On Petition for a Writ of Certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit |url=http://sblog.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Bank-Markazi-petition.pdf |publisher= |docket=14-770 |accessdate=<!-- stable document, irrelevant --> |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160503063641/http://sblog.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Bank-Markazi-petition.pdf |archivedate=May 3, 2016 |dead-url=no|via=SCOTUSblog}}</ref>{{Rp|60<!-- 13a -->}} affirmed, ''Peterson, et al. v. Islamic Republic of Iran, et al.'', 758&nbsp;[[Federal Reporter|F.3d]]&nbsp;185 ([[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit|2nd Cir.]], 2014)<ref name="Bank Markazi cert petition"/>{{Rp|48<!-- 1a -->}} |Subsequent= |Holding= A law that only applied to a specific case, identified by docket number, and eliminated all of the defenses one party had raised did not violate the separation of powers in the United States Constitution between the legislative (Congress) and judicial branches of government; since it pertained to the immunity of assets of a foreign state, it was also justified as a valid exercise of Congress' authority in foreign policy matters |SCOTUS=2016 |Majority=Ginsburg |JoinMajority=Kennedy, Breyer, Alito, Kagan; Thomas (except Part II-C) |Dissent=Roberts |JoinDissent=Sotomayor |LawsApplied=22 [[United States Code|U.S.C.]] §&nbsp;8772 }}
'''''Bank Markazi v. Peterson''''', 578 U.S. ___ (2016), was a [[Supreme Court of the United States|United States Supreme Court]] case that found that a law which only applied to a specific case, identified by [[Docket (court)|docket number]], and eliminated all of the defenses one party had raised does not violate the [[Separation of powers under the United States Constitution|separation of powers]] in the [[United States Constitution]] between the legislative ([[Congress of the United States|Congress]]) and [[judiciary|judicial]] branches of government. The [[plaintiff]]s in the [[trial court]], respondents in the Supreme Court, were several parties who had obtained [[Judgment (law)|judgments]] against [[Iran]] for its role in supporting [[state-sponsored terrorism]], particularly the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings]] and 1996 [[Khobar Towers bombing]], and sought [[Writ of execution|execution]] against a bank account in New York held, through European intermediaries, on behalf of [[Central Bank of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Bank Markazi]], the [[State ownership|state-owned]] [[Central Bank]] of Iran. The initial plaintiffs obtained court orders preventing the transfer of funds from the account in 2008 and initiated their lawsuit in 2010. Bank Markazi raised several defenses against the execution against the account, including that the account was not an asset ''of'' the bank, but rather an asset of its European intermediary, under both New York state property law and §201(a) of the [[Terrorism Risk Insurance Act]]. In response to concerns that existing laws were insufficient for the account to be used to settle the judgments, Congress included a section within a 2012 bill, [[Codification (law)|codified]] after enactment as 22 [[United States Code|U.S.C.]] §&nbsp;8772, that identified the pending lawsuit by docket number, applied only to the assets in the identified case, and essentially abrogated every legal basis available to Bank Markazi to prevent the plaintiffs from executing their claims against the account. Bank Markazi then argued that §&nbsp;8772 was an unconstitutional breach of the separation of power between the legislative and judicial branches of government, because it effectively directed a particular result in a single case without changing the generally applicable law. The [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]] and, on appeal, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] both upheld the constitutionality of §&nbsp;8772 and cleared the way for the plaintiffs to execute their judgments against the account, which held about $1.75&nbsp;billion in cash.
The United States Supreme Court granted [[certiorari]] and heard oral arguments in the case in January 2016, releasing their opinion in April 2016. A 6–2 majority found that §&nbsp;8772 was not unconstitutional, because it "changed the law by establishing new substantive standards"<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|18}}—essentially, that if Iran owns the assets, they would be available for execution against judgments against Iran—for the district court to apply to the case.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|18–19}} [[Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court|Justice]] [[Ruth Bader Ginsburg]], writing for the majority, explained that the federal judiciary has long upheld laws that affect one or a very small number of subjects as a valid exercise of Congress' legislative power<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|21}} and that the Supreme Court had previously upheld a statute that applied to cases identified by docket number in ''Robertson v. Seattle Audubon Society''&nbsp;(1992).<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|19}} The majority also upheld §&nbsp;8772 as a valid exercise of Congress' authority over foreign affairs. Prior to the enactment of the [[Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act]]&nbsp;(FSIA) in 1976, Congress and the Executive branch had authority to determine the immunity of foreign states from lawsuits. Despite transferring the authority to determine immunity to the courts through the FSIA, the majority contended that "it remains Congress' prerogative to alter a foreign state's immunity."<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|23}}
[[Chief Justice of the United States|Chief Justice]] [[John Roberts]], joined by Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]], dissented and harshly criticized the majority's holding. After providing historical context for the separation of powers between the legislature and judiciary found in [[Article III of the United States Constitution]], the Chief Justice explained that §&nbsp;8772 is a type of unconstitutional breach of the separation of powers between Congress and the judiciary "whereby Congress assumes the role of judge and decides a particular case in the first instance."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|7}} In his view, §&nbsp;8772 is no different than a hypothetical law applying to a case ''Smith v. Jones'' in which the legislature says simply "Smith wins". In the Chief Justice's view, §&nbsp;8772 was not a valid exercise of Congress' foreign affairs authority; he contended that Congress and the Executive branch have sufficient authority that they do not need to "seize" the judiciary's power to "make a political decision look like a judicial one."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|16}} Quoting [[James Madison]] in ''[[Federalist No. 48]]'', the Chief Justice lamented that this case "will indeed become a blueprint for extensive expansion of the legislative power at the judiciary's expense, feeding Congress's tendency to 'extend[] the sphere of its activity and draw[] all power into its impetuous vortex.'"<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|16–17}}
The decision came as Iran was seeking access to the world financial market just three months after [[sanctions against Iran|many sanctions]] were lifted as a result of Iran's compliance with [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|an agreement]] for curtailing development of [[Nuclear program of Iran|its nuclear enrichment program]]. Various Iranian officials denounced the decision as "theft",<ref name="Reuters: decision reaction"/> "a ridicule of law and justice",<ref name="Reuters: decision reaction"/> and "open hostility by the United States against the Iranian people."<ref name="AFP: Khamenei remarks"/> Iran announced that they would file suit against the United States in the [[International Court of Justice]] (ICJ) for reparations if the U.S. courts begin to "plunder"<ref name="NYT: ICJ action threatened"/> assets from the Citibank account to give to the winning plaintiffs, although it is not clear if the ICJ would have jurisdiction to entertain the case.
==Background==
===State immunity=== Foreign states generally enjoy [[state immunity|immunity from lawsuits]] in the United States under the [[Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act]] (FSIA). The FSIA is the exclusive basis for U.S. courts to exercise [[jurisdiction]] over a foreign government.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stewart|first1=David P.|title=The Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act: A Guide for Judges|date=2013|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|page=1|url=http://www.fjc.gov/public/pdf.nsf/lookup/fsiaguide2013.pdf/$file/fsiaguide2013.pdf|accessdate=31 May 2016|quote=The [FSIA] provides the exclusive basis for obtaining jurisdiction over these entities in U.S. courts (including special rules for service of process) and contains 'a comprehensive set of legal standards governing claims of immunity in every civil action against a foreign state or its political subdivisions, agencies, or instrumentalities.'}}</ref><ref>{{ussc|name=OBB Personenverkehr AG v. Sachs|link=OBB Personenverkehr AG v. Sachs|volume=577|year=2015|docket=13-1067|slip=3}}</ref> Prior to enactment of the FSIA in 1976, the executive branch was responsible for determining the immunity of foreign states on a case-by-case basis. By enacting the FSIA, Congress codified the guidelines for the immunity of foreign states and transferred responsibility for determining a foreign state's immunity from the executive branch to the judiciary.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Stewart|first1=David P.|title=The Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act: A Guide for Judges|date=2013|publisher=Federal Judicial Center|pages=5–6|url=http://www.fjc.gov/public/pdf.nsf/lookup/fsiaguide2013.pdf/$file/fsiaguide2013.pdf|accessdate=31 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{USC|28|1602}}</ref><ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|22–23}}
The FSIA contains an exception to the immunity of foreign states for victims of state-sponsored terrorism.<ref>{{USC|28|1605A}}</ref><ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|2–3}} Prior to 2002, if a judgment was awarded against a foreign government, only assets of the foreign government that were located in the U.S. and "used for commercial activity" could have been seized to satisfy the judgment.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|3}} To make judgments easier to enforce, Congress enacted the [[Terrorism Risk Insurance Act of 2002]] (TRIA) which allows judgments to be executed against "the blocked assets of [a] terrorist party."<ref name="TRIA 201(a)">{{cite act |title=Terrorism Risk Insurance Act of 2002 |type=Public Law |number=107-297 |language= |date=2002 |article=II, §201(a) |articletype=Title |page= |url=https://www.congress.gov/bill/107th-congress/house-bill/3210/text/pl |ref=}}</ref><ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|3}} Blocked assets include assets that may be seized by the [[President of the United States of America|President]] pursuant to his authority granted by [[United States Congress|Congress]].<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|4}}
===Litigation before §&nbsp;8772 was enacted <!-- Alternate (better?) title: Initial litigation against the Citibank account -->=== The suit involved more than 1300 individuals who had won several separate [[Judgment (law)|judgments]] against Iran for its supportive role in the [[1983 Beirut barracks bombings]], the 1996 [[Khobar Towers bombing]], several other bombings, an assassination, and a kidnapping.<ref name="Bank Markazi cert opposition">{{Cite report |authors=Liviu Voegel (Counsel of record)|date=2015 |title=In the Supreme Court of the United States: Bank Markazi, the Central Bank of Iran, Petitioner, v. Deborah D. Peterson, et al., Respondents; On Petition for a Writ of Certiorari to the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit: Brief in Opposition |url=http://sblog.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/106.-Brief-in-Opposition-to-Cert-Pet.pdf |publisher= |docket=14-770 |accessdate=<!-- stable document, irrelevant --> |format=PDF |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160531021805/http://sblog.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/106.-Brief-in-Opposition-to-Cert-Pet.pdf |archivedate=May 31, 2016 |dead-url=no|via=SCOTUSblog|display-authors=etal}}</ref>{{Rp|2}} After winning judgments [[Default judgment|by default]], based on a clear evidentiary basis for Iran's liability, they sought [[Writ of execution|writs of execution]] against a Citibank account in New York connected with Iran's [[central bank]].<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|6–8}} The suits for execution against the Citibank account were consolidated into one case through various procedural mechanisms.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|8}}
The named [[plaintiff]] in the case, Deborah Peterson, is the sister of a victim of the Beirut barracks bombings; joined by victims and other relatives of victims, she had won a default judgment in 2003 against Iran for its role in the bombings.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|6–7}}<ref>{{cite news|last1=Ford|first1=Matt|title=What the Supreme Court's Ruling on Iranian Assets Means|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2016/04/bank-markazi/479190/|accessdate=23 April 2016|work=The Atlantic|date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> Because of the large number of plaintiffs in the case—almost 1,000—the judge appointed [[special master]]s to determine each plaintiff's right to collect damages and appropriate amount of damages; in 2007, the judge entered a default judgment against Iran for $2,656,944,877 in damages.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Peterson v. Islamic Republic of Iran |vol=515 |reporter=F.Supp.2d |opinion=25 |pinpoint=60 |court=[[United States District Court for the District of Columbia]] |date=2007 |url=https://scholar.google.com/scholar_case?case=6534369202265363549&hl=en&as_sdt=6&as_vis=1&oi=scholarr |accessdate=April 28, 2016 |quote=ORDERED that Default Judgment be entered in favor of plaintiffs and against defendants, jointly and severally, in the amount of $2,656,944,877.00}}</ref>
{{multiple image | align = right | direction = vertical | width = 200 | header = | image1 = USMC Barracks Lebanon 1983 Photo.jpg | alt1 = oblique, aerial image in black-and-white of a large, rectangular building <!-- | caption1 = The [[United States Marine Corps|USMC]] barracks before the 1983 bombing --> | image2 = USMC-Lebanon82-97.jpg | alt2 = black-and-white image of men digging through rubble <!-- | caption2 = The Marine Corps barracks after the 1983 bombing --> | footer = The [[United States Marine Corps|USMC]] barracks before and after the 1983 bombing }} In 2008, the plaintiffs first learned of the interests of the [[Central Bank of the Islamic Republic of Iran|Central Bank of Iran (Bank Markazi)]] in a [[Citibank]] bank account in [[New York (state)|New York]] and obtained orders restraining the transfer of funds from the account.<ref name="2nd Circuit opinion">{{cite court |litigants=Peterson v. Islamic Republic of Iran |vol= 758|reporter=F.3d |opinion=185 |pinpoint= |court=[[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] |date=2014 |url=http://cases.justia.com/federal/appellate-courts/ca2/13-2952/13-2952-2014-07-09.pdf?ts=1410919507 |accessdate=April 28, 2016 |quote=<!-- When plaintiffs first learned of Bank Markazi's interest in the assets in 2008, they obtained restraints against transfer of the assets. -->}}</ref>{{Rp|3}} The account consisted of [[Bond (finance)|bonds]] and belonged to a [[Luxembourg]]-based bank, [[Clearstream|Clearstream Banking, S.A.]], which held the account on behalf of Bank Markazi and deposited interest from the bonds into Bank Markazi's Clearstream account.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|9}} At some point in 2008, an account for Bank Markazi was opened with Italian bank [[Banca UBAE]]<!-- there in no WP article, but this is a viable potential article per linking policy (many search results about the bank's financing of Arab governments) --> to place the interest payments from the Clearstream account, placing a second intermediary between Bank Markazi and the Citibank account.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|9}} By the time of the Supreme Court hearing, the Citibank account held about $1.75&nbsp;billion in cash, as the last of the bonds had matured in April 2012.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|9 <!-- (fn. 11) -->}} In 2010, the plaintiffs initiated their lawsuit against Bank Markazi, Clearstream, Banca UBAE, and Citibank, jointly, seeking to execute against the Citibank account their judgments for damages against Iran, based on §201(a) of the TRIA, which provides that when "a person has obtained a judgment against a terrorist party&nbsp;... the blocked assets of that terrorist party (including the blocked assets of any agency or instrumentality of that terrorist party) shall be subject to execution or attachment."<ref name="TRIA 201(a)"/><ref name="2nd Circuit opinion"/>{{Rp|3}}
In February 2012, President [[Barack Obama|Obama]] froze all assets of the Iranian government in the U.S., which included the Citibank account alleged to be controlled by Bank Markazi.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|4}}<ref name="SCOTUSblog: April 2015">{{cite web|last1=Denniston|first1=Lyle|title=Court seeks U.S. views on terrorism case|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2015/04/court-seeks-u-s-views-on-terrorism-case/|website=SCOTUSblog|accessdate=23 April 2016|date=April 6, 2015}}</ref> However, there were concerns that existing laws were insufficient for the account to be used to settle the judgments.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|5}} Bank Markazi claimed that the account was not an asset ''of'' Bank Markazi, but its intermediary, Clearstream, in relation to both TRIA and New York state property law.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|4 <!-- (fn. 3) -->}}
===Section 8772=== Due to the issues raised in the case, Congress included a section within the Iran Threat Reduction and Syria Human Rights Act, [[Codification (law)|codified]] as 22 U.S.C. §&nbsp;8772, that preempted any state law and provided that:<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|5–6}} {{quote|a financial asset that is— :(A) held in the United States for a foreign securities intermediary doing business in the United States; :(B) a blocked asset (whether or not subsequently unblocked) that is property described in subsection (b); and :(C) equal in value to a financial asset of Iran, including an asset of the central bank or monetary authority of the Government of Iran or any agency or instrumentality of that Government, that such foreign securities intermediary or a related intermediary holds abroad
shall be subject to execution or attachment in aid of execution in order to satisfy any judgment to the extent of any compensatory damages awarded against Iran for damages for personal injury or death caused by an act of torture, extrajudicial killing, aircraft sabotage, or hostage-taking, or the provision of material support or resources for such an act.|22 U.S.C. §&nbsp;8772(a)(1)<!-- <ref>{{USCSub|22|8772|a|1}}</ref> -->}}
In response to concerns the banking industry had to early drafts of the legislation,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Herszenhorn|first1=David|title=Iran Compensation Case Pits Congress Against the Supreme Court|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/20/us/politics/iran-compensation-case-pits-congress-against-the-supreme-court.html?_r=0|accessdate=3 May 2016|work=The New York Times|date=January 19, 2016}}</ref> §&nbsp;8772 specified the assets that the section pertains to as: {{quote|The financial assets described in this section are the financial assets that are identified in and the subject of proceedings in the United States District Court for the Southern District of New York in Peterson et al. v. Islamic Republic of Iran et al., Case No. 10 Civ. 4518 (BSJ) (GWG), that were restrained by restraining notices and levies secured by the plaintiffs in those proceedings, as modified by court order dated June 27, 2008, and extended by court orders dated June 23, 2009, May 10, 2010, and June 11, 2010, so long as such assets remain restrained by court order.|22 U.S.C. §&nbsp;8772(b)<!-- <ref>{{USCSub|22|8772|b}}</ref> -->}}
Section&nbsp;8772 also specified that the courts needed to identify "whether Iran holds equitable title to, or the beneficial interest in, the assets&nbsp;...and that no other person possesses a constitutionally protected interest in the assets&nbsp;...under the [[Fifth Amendment to the Constitution of the United States]]."<ref>{{USCSub|22|8772|a|2}}</ref> If another person held a constitutionally protected interest in the assets, their interest in the assets would not be infringed by the law.<ref>{{USCSub|22|8772|a|2|B}}</ref>
===After §&nbsp;8772 was enacted=== Section&nbsp;8772 eliminated all of Bank Markazi's defenses to the seizure of the account's assets, valued at approximately $1.75&nbsp;billion.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|7–8}} Bank Markazi conceded that they held "equitable title to, or beneficial interest in, the assets", per §8772(a)(2)(A), but then claimed that §&nbsp;8772 violated the separation of powers in the United States Constitution between the legislative (Congress) and judicial branches of government.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|10}} The [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York]] and, on appeal, the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit]] both upheld the constitutionality of §&nbsp;8772 and awarded the assets to the plaintiffs.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|7, 10–12}}
==Appeal to the Supreme Court of the United States== On December 29, 2014,<ref name="SCOTUS docket">{{cite web|title=Docket No. 14-770|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/Search.aspx?FileName=/docketfiles/14-770.htm|website=Supreme Court of the United States|accessdate=30 April 2016}}</ref> Bank Markazi filed a petition for [[certiorari]] with the [[Supreme Court of the United States]], requesting the Court to consider the question: Does §&nbsp;8772 violate the separation of powers by purporting to change the law for, and directing a particular result in, a single pending case?<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|1}} The certiorari petition was circulated to the Justices for their conference on April 3, 2015, after a brief by the respondents (Peterson) opposing certiorari and a reply brief from the petitioner (Bank Markazi) were filed in March.<ref name="SCOTUS docket"/> Following the April 3rd conference, the Court called for the [[Solicitor General of the United States#Call for the Views of the Solicitor General|Solicitor General to file a brief]] expressing the views of the federal government, which was filed on August 19.<ref name="SCOTUS docket"/> In May and June, the Supreme Court meets only to issue orders and opinions and does not hear oral arguments until the next term begins.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Court and Its Procedures|url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/about/procedures.aspx|website=Supreme Court of the United States|accessdate=1 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McElroy|first1=Lisa|title=Summer at the Supreme Court: In Plain English|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2010/07/summer-at-the-supreme-court-in-plain-english/|website=SCOTUSblog|accessdate=1 May 2016|date=July 7, 2010}}</ref> The Court granted certiorari following its conference on September 28.<ref name="SCOTUS docket"/>
Oral arguments were held on January 13, 2016 with appearances by [[Jeffrey Lamken]]<!-- notable lawyer, so a redlink to encourage creation of an article for him is merited --> for the petitioner, [[Theodore Olson]] for the respondents, and Deputy Solicitor General [[Edwin Kneedler]] for the United States as ''[[amicus curiae]]''.<ref name="SCOTUS docket"/> Justice [[Antonin Scalia]] was present during oral arguments.<ref>{{Cite report |author=United States Supreme Court |date=2016 |title=In the Supreme Court of the United States: Bank Markazi, aka the Central Bank of Iran, petitioner v. Deborah Peterson, et al.; No. 14-770 |url=https://www.supremecourt.gov/oral_arguments/argument_transcripts/14-770_m64o.pdf |type=Transcript of oral arguments |format=PDF |editor-last=Alderson Court Reporting |page=7 |docket=14-770 |accessdate=May 8, 2016<!-- included because the version accessed says "Official - Subject to Final Review" --> |quote= }}</ref> He passed away in February,<ref>{{cite news|last1=Liptak|first1=Adam|title=Antonin Scalia, Justice on the Supreme Court, Dies at 79|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/02/14/us/antonin-scalia-death.html?_r=0|accessdate=8 May 2016|work=New York Times|date=February 13, 2016}}</ref> voiding his vote in the initial vote on the case's outcome and precluding any draft opinion he may have written from being published by the Court.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sherman|first1=Mark|last2=Hananel|first2=Sam|title=Court looking at extended period with only eight justices on the bench, producing tie votes|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2016-02-15/results-in-key-cases-could-change-with-scalias-death|accessdate=8 May 2016|work=U.S. News & World Report|agency=Associated Press|date=February 15, 2016|quote=Scalia's votes and draft opinions in pending cases no longer matter. Veteran Supreme Court lawyer Roy Englert says that 'the vote of a deceased justice does not count.' Nothing is final at the court until it is released publicly and, while it is rare, justices have flipped their votes and the outcomes in some cases.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author1=Goldstein, Tom|authorlink1=Tom Goldstein|title=What happens to this Term's close cases? (Updated)|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2016/02/what-happens-to-this-terms-close-cases/|accessdate=8 May 2016|work=SCOTUSblog|date=February 13, 2016|quote=Votes that the Justice cast in cases that have not been publicly decided are void.}}</ref> The Court's 6-2 opinion was delivered on April 20, 2016.<ref name="SCOTUS docket"/>
==Oral argument==
On January 13, 2016, during oral argument with [[Theodore Olson]], Chief Justice [[John Roberts]] said: {{quote| And just so you understand what I'm concerned about. You know, there are places in the world where courts function just the way our courts do, except every now and then, when there's a case that the -- the strong man who runs the country is interested in because a crony is one of the parties or whatever, and he picks up the phone and he tells the court, You decide this case this way.
And I don't care what you thought the law was, decide it this way.|Bank Markazi, oral argument}}
His dissenting opinion is discussed in detail below.
==Opinion of the Court== [[File:Ruth Bader Ginsburg, official SCOTUS portrait, crop.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|alt=headshot portrait of Justice Ginsburg|Justice Ginsburg, who authored the majority opinion]] Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg wrote the majority opinion, which held that §&nbsp;8772 does not infringe on the separation of powers between the legislative and judicial branches of government, considering also that the law is an exercise of congressional authority regarding foreign affairs.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/> Justice [[Anthony Kennedy]], Justice [[Clarence Thomas]], Justice [[Stephen Breyer]], Justice [[Samuel Alito]], and Justice [[Elena Kagan]] joined the majority opinion (however, Justice Thomas did not join as to Part II-C of the opinion).<ref name="SCOTUS docket"/>
The majority began by explaining that judiciary's authority under [[Article III of the United States Constitution]] is to "'say what the law is'", quoting ''[[Marbury v. Madison]]'' (1803).<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|12}} "Congress, no doubt, may not usurp a court's power to interpret and apply the law to the circumstances before it"<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 12 (internal citations omitted)</ref> by, for example, saying in a hypothetical case ''Smith v. Jones'' that Smith wins<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|12–13 <!-- (n. 13) -->}} or compelling the courts to reexamine a case after final judgment has been issued.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|13}}
Bank Markazi relied on ''[[United States v. Klein]]'' (1871) for much of its argument.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Morrison, Alan|authorlink1=Alan Morrison (lawyer)|title=Bank Markazi v. Peterson – Equity and Justice versus the Separation of Powers|url=http://www.gwlr.org/bank-markazi-v-peterson-equity-and-justice-versus-the-separation-of-powers/|website=[[The George Washington Law Review]]|publisher=[[The George Washington University Law School]]|date=April 21, 2016}}</ref> In ''Klein'', the Court questioned whether "'the legislature may prescribe rules of decision to the Judicial Department&nbsp;... in cases pending before it.'"<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 15 (quoting ''Klein'', 13 Wall., at 146)</ref> The majority found that "[o]ne cannot take this language from ''Klein'' at face value"<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 15 (internal citations omitted)</ref> because the power of Congress to make retroactive laws applicable to pending cases has long been recognized.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|15}} The majority explained that the contemporary significance of ''Klein'' is that "Congress may not exercise its authority, including its power to regulate federal jurisdiction, in a way that requires [federal courts]...to become active participants in violating the Constitution."<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 15 n. 19 (internal citations omitted)</ref> The unfairness of any retroactive legislation is "'not a sufficient reason for a court to fail to give that law its intended scope.'"<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 16 (quoting ''Landgraf v. USI Film Products'', 511 U.S. 244, 267–268 (1994))</ref> The Constitution contains only limited constraints on the enactment of retroactive legislation: {{quote|The [[Ex Post Facto Clause]] flatly prohibits retroactive application of penal legislation. Article I, §10, cl. 1, prohibits States from passing&nbsp;... laws '[[Contract Clause#Modification of private contracts|impairing the Obligation of Contracts]].' The [[Fifth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fifth Amendment]]'s [[Takings Clause]] prevents the Legislature (and other government actors) from depriving private persons of vested property rights except for a 'public use' and upon payment of 'just compensation.' [[Bill of attainder#United States|The prohibitions]] of '[[Bill of attainder|Bills of Attainder]]' in Art. I, <!-- quoted text uses two section symbols -->§§9–10, prohibit legislatures from singling out summary punishment for past conduct. The [[Due Process Clause]] also protects the interests in fair notice and repose that may be compromised by retroactive legislation; a justification sufficient to validate a statute's prospective application under the Clause 'may not suffice' to warrant its retroactive application.|''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 16 (2016) (quoting ''Landgraf v. USI Film Products'', 511 U.S. 244, 266–267 (1994))}} The majority affirmed that "Congress may indeed direct courts to apply newly enacted, outcome-altering legislation in pending civil cases,"<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|16}} citing its previous decisions in ''[[Plaut v. Spendthrift Farm, Inc.]]''&nbsp;(1995), ''[[Robertson v. Seattle Audubon Society]]''&nbsp;(1992), and ''[[Landgraf v. USI Film Products]]''&nbsp;(1994).<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|16}} Accordingly, the majority found that §&nbsp;8772 "changed the law by establishing new substantive standards"<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|18}}—essentially, that if Iran owns the assets, they would be available for execution against judgments against Iran—for the district court to apply to the case.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|18–19}} Section&nbsp;8772 left several issues for the District Court to adjudicate: it did not define its key terms "beneficial interest" and "equitable title"; whether any other party had a constitutionally protected interest in the account; and whether the assets were "held in the United States" (Clearstream argued the assets were located in Luxembourg, not New York).<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|17}}
The fact that the law only applied to one case does not change its validity,<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|20–22}} although the majority conceded that a narrowly crafted law affecting just one person or a limited number of people may violate the [[Equal Protection Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]] "if arbitrary or inadequately justified."<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|21 <!-- (n. 27) -->}} The federal judiciary has long upheld laws that affect one or a very small number of subjects as a valid exercise of Congress' legislative power,<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|21}} and the Supreme Court upheld a statute that applied to cases identified by docket number in ''Robertson v. Seattle Audubon Society''&nbsp;(1992).<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|19}}
The final portion of the majority's opinion, in which Justice Thomas did not join,<ref name="SCOTUS docket"/> upheld §&nbsp;8772 as a valid exercise of Congress' authority to regulate foreign affairs.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|22}} Citing ''[[Dames & Moore v. Regan]]''&nbsp;(1981), a case which also involved the availability of Iranian assets for execution of judgments against Iran,<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Dames & Moore v. Regan |vol=453 |reporter=U.S. |opinion=654 |pinpoint=662–668 |date=1981 |url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/453/654.html |accessdate=May 1, 2016 |quote=}}</ref> the majority points out that regulating foreign-state<!-- hyphenated, because it could be read as foreign "state assets" (eg. assets of the U.S. located abroad) --> assets—e.g. by blocking them or regulating their availability for execution against judgments—has never been found to violate the judiciary's authority. Prior to the enactment of the Foreign Sovereign Immunities Act (FSIA), the Executive branch routinely made case-specific determinations of the scope of immunity for foreign states.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|23}} Those decisions were not rejected as infringements on the judiciary's authority. Although the enactment of the FSIA in 1976 transferred authority to the courts to determine foreign-state immunity, the majority held that "it remains Congress' prerogative to alter a foreign state's immunity."<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|23}} When Congress enacted §&nbsp;8772, it "acted comfortably within the political branches' authority over foreign sovereign immunity and foreign-state assets."<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|23}}
===Chief Justice Roberts' dissenting opinion=== [[File:File-Official roberts CJ cropped.jpg|thumb|upright=0.6|alt=headshot portrait of Chief Justice Roberts|Chief Justice Roberts wrote a dissenting opinion]] Chief Justice John Roberts, joined by Justice [[Sonia Sotomayor]], dissented from the majority's ruling. It was the first time that Roberts and Sotomayor were the only two dissenters in a case; they had been on the court together since 2009.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mauro|first1=Tony|title=Roberts and Sotomayor: Odd Couple Dissents in Iran Bank Case|url=http://www.nationallawjournal.com/id=1202755457578/Roberts-and-Sotomayor-Odd-Couple-Dissents-in-Iran-Bank-Case?mcode=1202615705846&slreturn=20160328003904|accessdate=28 April 2016|work=The National Law Journal|date=April 20, 2016|quote=Ever since Sonia Sotomayor joined the U.S. Supreme Court in 2009, she and Chief Justice John Roberts Jr. have never been the only two dissenters in a case. Until Wednesday.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Howe|first1=Amy|title=Thursday round-up|url=http://www.scotusblog.com/2016/04/thursday-round-up-320/|website=[[SCOTUSblog]]|accessdate=28 April 2016|date=April 21, 2016}}</ref>
Roberts began his argument with an analogy: {{quote|Imagine your neighbor sues you, claiming that your fence is on his property. His evidence is a letter from the previous owner of your home, accepting your neighbor's version of the facts. Your defense is an official county map, which under state law establishes the boundaries of your land. The map shows the fence on your side of the property line. You also argue that your neighbor's claim is six months outside the statute of limitations.
Now imagine that while the lawsuit is pending, your neighbor persuades the legislature to enact a new statute. The new statute provides that for your case, and your case alone, a letter from one neighbor to another is conclusive of property boundaries, and the statute of limitations is one year longer. Your neighbor wins. Who would you say decided your case: the legislature, which targeted your specific case and eliminated your specific defenses so as to ensure your neighbor's victory, or the court, which presided over the ''fait accompli''?
That question lies at the root of the case the Court confronts today.|''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 1 (2016) (Roberts, C.J., dissenting)}} In the Chief Justice's view, §&nbsp;8772 violates the separation of powers in Article III "[n]o less than if [Congress] had passed a law saying 'respondents win.'"<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|1–2}} The majority responded that a more appropriate analogy to the case is if a legislature enacts a law specifying that a 2000 map supersedes a 1990 map in an ongoing property dispute in which the parties are contesting whether an ambiguous statute makes a 1990 or 2000 county map the authoritative source for establishing property boundaries.<ref name="Slip opinion majority"/>{{Rp|19}}
The Chief Justice proceeded to detail the origin, purpose, and case law history of the separation of powers. [[Article Three of the United States Constitution]] establishes an independent judiciary with "distinct and inviolable authority."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|2}} Such separation of powers "safeguards individual freedom."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|2}} As [[Alexander Hamilton]] wrote in ''[[Federalist No. 78]]'', quoting [[Montesquieu]], "'there is no liberty if the power of judging be not separated from the legislative and executive powers.'"<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|2–3}} The separation of powers between the judiciary and legislative branches was examined in detail in ''Plaut v. Spendthrift Farm, Inc.'' (1995),<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|3}} in which the Supreme Court found unconstitutional a statute that reopened a case after a final judgment.<ref>{{cite court |litigants=Plaut v. Spendthrift Farm, Inc. |vol=514 |reporter=U.S. |opinion=211 |pinpoint= |court=United States Supreme Court |date=1995 |url=https://caselaw.findlaw.com/us-supreme-court/514/211.html |accessdate=May 2, 2016 |quote=}}</ref> At the time of the framing of the Constitution, judicial and legislative powers were often intermingled. The colonial legislatures often performed many of the functions of the judiciary, such as functioning as the [[Supreme court|court of last resort]], granting new trials, and providing [[Trial court<!-- Original jurisdiction -->|original review]], [[Appellate court<!-- Appellate jurisdiction -->|appellate review]], [[Stay of proceedings|stays of judgments]], and providing other types of relief "in an effort to do what is agreeable to Right and Justice."<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 3 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (internal citations omitted)</ref> The colonial charters of [[Province of Massachusetts Bay|Massachusetts]], [[Connecticut Colony|Connecticut]], and [[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations|Rhode Island]] gave the legislatures the authority of court of last resort.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|3}} In New Hampshire, judicial appeals were directed to the governor and his council, but routinely referred to the legislature for discussion.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|4}} And for over half a century, the colonial assembly of Virginia could review court judgments.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|4}} The involvement of legislatures in judicial matters "intensified during the American Revolution,"<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|4}} which "soon prompted a sense of a sharp necessity to separate the legislative from the judicial power."<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 4 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (internal citations omitted)</ref> The interference of the legislatures in judicial matters "figur[ed] prominently in the [[Founding Fathers of the United States|Framers']] decision to devise a system for securing liberty through the division of power."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|5}} This resulted in Article Three of the United States Constitution, which forms the "central pillar of judicial independence"<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|6}} and places "'[t]he judicial Power of the United States'&nbsp;... in 'one supreme Court', and in such 'inferior Courts'"<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 6 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (quoting ''U.S. Const. art. III, §1'')</ref> as Congress may establish.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|6}} This judicial power extends "to all Cases, in Law and Equity, arising under this Constitution, the Laws of the United States, and Treaties made, or which shall be made, under their Authority."<ref>{{cite act |title=United States Constitution |type=empty |date=1787 |article=III, §2 |articletype=Article |url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Constitution_of_the_United_States_of_America#Article_III|ref=}}</ref>
The Chief Justice explained that there are three types of unconstitutional restrictions on the power of the judiciary.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|6}} "'Congress cannot vest review of the decisions of Article III courts in officials of the Executive Branch'",<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 7 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (quoting ''Chicago & Southern Air Lines, Inc. v. Waterman SS Corp.'', 333 U.S. 103, 113 (1948))</ref> or "'retroactively command the federal courts to reopen final judgments.'"<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 7 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (quoting ''Plaut'', 514 U.S., at 218-219)</ref> In the Chief Justice's view, this case is a third type of unconstitutional interference with the judiciary's authority, "whereby Congress assumes the role of judge and decides a particular case in the first instance,"<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|7}} which he believes is precisely what §&nbsp;8772 does.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|7}} Section&nbsp;8772 foreclosed Bank Markazi's defenses that it was immune from prosecution under the FSIA, a separate [[Legal personality|juridical entity]] under both U.S. federal common law and international law and thus not liable for Iran's debts, and that New York state law did not permit execution of the plaintiff's judgments against its assets.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|7}} "And lest there be any doubt that Congress' sole concern was deciding this particular case&nbsp;... §&nbsp;8772 provided that nothing in the statute 'shall be construed&nbsp;... to affect the availability, or lack thereof, of a right to satisfy a judgment in any other action against a terrorist party in any proceedings other than' [this case]."<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 7 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (quoting {{USCSub|22|8772|c}})</ref>
In the hypothetical case of ''Smith v. Jones'' in which Congress enacted a statute that says "Smith wins", the majority would find it unconstitutional because it "would create no new substantive law."<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 12-13 (n. 17)</ref><!-- <ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|11}} --> In the Chief Justice's view, it would: before the passage of the hypothetical statute, the law did not provide that Smith wins; after passage of the hypothetical statute, it does. For the Chief Justice, "the question is whether its action constitutes an exercise of judicial power."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|12}} Both the hypothetical "Smith wins" statute and §&nbsp;8772 both have the same effect, which is essentially the legislature's "'policy judgment'"<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 12 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (quoting ''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 18)</ref> that one side in the case wins.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|12}} He compared the majority's opinion, which found that §&nbsp;8772 left plenty of issues for the District Court to adjudicate, to "a constitutional [[Maginot Line]], easily circumvented by the simplest maneuver of taking away every defense against Smith's victory, without saying 'Smith wins.'"<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|12}} Section&nbsp;8772 only required the courts to make two decisions—that Bank Markazi had an equitable interest in the assets and no one else did—that were both already clear before §&nbsp;8772 was enacted.<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|12}} By the majority's view of "plenty",<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 12 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (citing ''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 16-17 and n. 20)</ref> the Chief Justice contended that, in the hypothetical case ''Smith v. Jones'', the majority would uphold a judgment for Smith if the court finds that Jones was [[Service of process|served notice of the lawsuit]] and the case was within the [[statute of limitations]].<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|12–13}} Strongly criticizing the majority, the Chief Justice, quoting ''[[Federalist No. 48]]'', concluded that the majority's "failure to enforce [the boundary between the judicial and legislative branches] in a case as clear as this reduces Article III to a mere 'parchment barrier against the encroaching spirit' of legislative power."<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 14 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (quoting ''Federalist No. 48'')</ref>
Finally, the Chief Justice distinguished this case from ''Dames & Moore''. The actions of the president that ''Dames & Moore'' upheld did not dictate the outcome of the case, but merely specified that the claims be handled by [[Iran–United States Claims Tribunal|a different tribunal]].<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|15}} The court's decision in ''Dames & Moore'' was based on the "longstanding practice of settling the claims of U.S. nationals against foreign countries by treaty or executive agreement."<ref>''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 15 (Roberts, C.J., dissenting) (internal citations omitted) (citing ''Dames & Moore'', 453 U.S., at 679)</ref> In contrast with the majority's interpretation of ''Dames & Moore'', "those dispositions, crucially, were not exercises of judicial power."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|15}} The Chief Justice critiqued the majority's position on ''Dames & Moore'' by contending that the political branches of the government—Congress and the executive branch—have sufficient power of their own to address the issues in this case and do not need to "commandeer[] the courts to make a political decision look like a judicial one."<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|16}}
The Chief Justice concluded with a strong criticism of the majority's decision:<ref name="Slip opinion dissent"/>{{Rp|16–17}} {{quote|At issue here is a basic principle, not a technical rule. Section&nbsp;8772 decides this case no less certainly than if Congress had directed entry of judgment for respondents. As a result, the potential of the decision today 'to effect important change in the equilibrium of power' is 'immediately evident.' ''[[Morrison v. Olson]]'', 487 U.S. 654, 699 (1988) (Scalia, J., dissenting) Hereafter, with this Court's seal of approval, Congress can unabashedly pick the winners and losers in particular pending cases. Today's decision will indeed become a 'blueprint for extensive expansion of the legislative power' at the Judiciary's expense, ''[[:wikisource:Metropolitan Washington Airports Authority v. Citizens for the Abatement of Aircraft Noise Inc./Opinion of the Court|Metropolitan Washington Airports Authority v. Citizens for Abatement of Aircraft Noise, Inc.]]'', 501 U.S. 252, 277 (1991), feeding Congress's tendency to 'extend[] the sphere of its activity and draw[] all power into its impetuous vortex,' The Federalist No. 48&nbsp;... ([[James Madison|J. Madison]])|''Bank Markazi'', slip op. at 16–17 (2016) (Roberts, C.J., dissenting)}}
==<span id="Political aftermath">Subsequent developments</span>== ===Payout to plaintiff-respondents=== The ruling clears the way for the plaintiff-respondents to collect from the roughly $1.75&nbsp;billion bank account, which will be enough to satisfy about 70% of their collective $2.5&nbsp;billion in judgments.<ref name="Law360 Weinberger"/><ref name="NYT: ICJ action threatened"/> They will not be eligible to collect from a $1&nbsp;billion fund—the Victims of State Sponsored Terrorism Fund—established by Congress in 2015 to pay victims of state-sponsored terrorism. That fund pays 30% of judgments until all applicants have received that amount; remaining funds will not be distributed until all claimants have received 30% of their judgment.<ref name="Law360 Weinberger"/><ref>{{USCSub|42|10609|d|3|B}}</ref>
===Legal community reactions=== Attorney and law professor [[Alan Morrison (lawyer)|Alan Morrison]], writing for ''[[The George Washington Law Review]]'', remarked that:<ref name="GWLR: Morrison"/> {{quote|To a non-lawyer trying to decide who should win just on the equity, the Bank’s chances did not look very good, and on April 20, 2016, the Supreme Court ... upheld the constitutionality of § 8772, thereby removing a major barrier to the victims collecting at least some of their judgments. Those were the atmospherics, but on the legal issues, there was substantial agreement between the two opinions, although in their conclusions they were very far apart. All of the Justices agreed that Congress could pass laws changing the existing law and make those changes generally applicable to pending cases, provided it did so clearly. They also agreed that Congress could not pass a law in a pending case that said something along the lines of, “The Court is directed to enter judgment for the plaintiff,” or that “The plaintiff wins and defendant loses.” To do so would usurp the judicial role and improperly expand that of Congress. Nor could Congress change the law in a way that re-opened a case in which there was a final judgment not subject to further appeal. There was also agreement that Congress could write laws that applied to a limited category of cases, at least in those cases in which only the Government was adversely affected by the change in the law. The issue here was where § 8772 fell on that spectrum.}} Morrison expressed "concern ... that what happened here will repeat itself in other circumstances in which the equities [are] quite different".<ref name="GWLR: Morrison"/> Although Morrison suggested that an individual aggrieved by such a law could bring a claim for relief under the [[Equal Protection Clause]] of the [[Fourteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution|Fourteenth Amendment]], he argued that such a claim is unlikely to be successful because the law will likely be upheld when reviewed under the [[Rational basis review|rational basis test]].<ref name="GWLR: Morrison">{{cite web|author1=Morrison, Alan B.|authorlink1=Alan Morrison (lawyer)|title=Bank Markazi v. Peterson – Equity and Justice versus the Separation of Powers|url=http://www.gwlr.org/bank-markazi-v-peterson-equity-and-justice-versus-the-separation-of-powers/|website=[[The George Washington Law Review]]|publisher=[[George Washington University Law School]]|accessdate=19 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619124847/http://www.gwlr.org/bank-markazi-v-peterson-equity-and-justice-versus-the-separation-of-powers/|archivedate=June 19, 2016|date=April 21, 2016|deadurl=no}}</ref> The rational basis test asks "there is some rational relationship between disparity of treatment and some legitimate governmental purpose."<ref>''Heller v. Doe'', [https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/509/312/case.html 509 U.S. 312], 320 (1993)</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=History of Equal Protection and the Levels of Review|url=http://nationalparalegal.edu/conLawCrimProc_Public/EqualProtection/HistoryOfEqualProtection.asp|publisher=National Paralegal College|accessdate=19 June 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160324192735/http://nationalparalegal.edu/conlawcrimproc_public/EqualProtection/HistoryOfEqualProtection.asp|archivedate=March 24, 2016|deadurl=no}}</ref>
Law professor Evan Zoldan, writing in the ''Yale Law & Policy Review Inter Alia'', noted that the ruling allowed Congress to pick a winner in a particular pending case. He wrote that "By permitting Congress to direct judgment in favor of victims of terrorism, the Bank Markazi Court helped compensate hundreds of people who suffered great tragedies. But, perhaps inadvertently, the Court also conferred on Congress the expansive, and dangerous, power to target an individual for special treatment that is not applied to the population in general."<ref>{{cite web|last1=Zoldan|first1=Evan|title=Bank Markazi and the Undervaluation of Legislative Generality|url=http://ylpr.yale.edu/inter_alia/bank-markazi-and-undervaluation-legislative-generality|website=Yale Law & Policy Review|publisher=Yale Law School|accessdate=February 12, 2017}}</ref>
According to Stuart Newberger, an attorney who represents terror victims, the ruling could hinder foreign governments from using the judiciary to override determinations by Congress and the President regarding the availability of their assets to satisfy judgments against them.<ref name="Law360 Weinberger"/> Newberger praised the ruling as "a message for any country that if Congress and the president take steps to freeze assets, make assets available to victims, that the courts are going to defer."<ref name="Law360 Weinberger">{{cite news|last1=Weinberger|first1=Evan|title=Iran Bank Ruling Will Keep Courts Out Of Foreign Affairs|url=https://www.crowell.com/files/20160420-Iran-Bank-Ruling-Will-Keep-Courts-Out-Of-Foreign-Affairs-Newberger.pdf|accessdate=8 June 2016|work=[[Law360]]|date=April 20, 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160608024252/https://www.crowell.com/files/20160420-Iran-Bank-Ruling-Will-Keep-Courts-Out-Of-Foreign-Affairs-Newberger.pdf|archivedate=June 8, 2016|deadurl=no|format=PDF}}</ref>
===U.S. reactions=== The decision was praised in the U.S. by the litigants, their counsel, and politicians. Theodore Olson, counsel for the respondents, praised the ruling, saying it "will bring long-overdue relief to ... victims of Iranian terrorism and their families, many of whom have waited decades for redress."<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kendall|first1=Brent|title=Supreme Court Upholds Terrorism Victims’ Ability to Collect Frozen Iran Funds|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-upholds-terrorism-victims-ability-to-collect-frozen-iran-funds-1461162784|accessdate=19 June 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 20, 2016|quote=Lawyer Theodore Olson, who argued the case for the victims, said the high court’s decision holds Iran accountable for supporting terrorism and 'will bring long-overdue relief to more than 1,000 victims of Iranian terrorism and their families, many of whom have waited decades for redress.'|subscription=yes}}</ref> Praising the court's decision, lead plaintiff Deborah Peterson found solace that "in the eyes of the law, we know who is responsible, and those who are responsible have been brought to the justice that we are capable of bringing them to here on earth."<ref name="WP: 20 April">{{cite news|last1=Barnes|first1=Robert|title=Supreme Court allows families of terrorism victims to collect Iranian assets|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/courts_law/supreme-court-allows-families-of-terrorism-victims-to-college-iranian-assets/2016/04/20/6793f0cc-0703-11e6-a12f-ea5aed7958dc_story.html?hpid=hp_rhp-more-top-stories_no-name%3Ahomepage%2Fstory|accessdate=19 June 2016|work=Washington Post|date=April 20, 2016}}</ref>
Law professor [[Jimmy Gurulé]] said the decision "sends a powerful message to rogue states and state sponsors of terrorism that if you, directly or indirectly, provide material support for terrorism, you will be held accountable"<ref name="WP: 20 April"/>—sentiment echoed by [[Mark Dubowitz]], director of the [[Foundation for Defense of Democracies]]<ref name="CNN: 20 April">{{cite news|last1=de Vogue|first1=Ariane|title=Supreme Court rules in favor of terror victims|url=http://www.cnn.com/2016/04/20/politics/supreme-court-rules-in-favor-of-terror-victims/index.html|accessdate=19 June 2016|work=CNN|date=April 20, 2016|quote='From a public policy perspective, the Iranian government needs to be punished for its support of past acts of terrorism,' said Mark Dubowitz, the executive director of the Foundation for Defense of Democracies, a group that filed a brief in support of Peterson. 'Governments need to know that if they are going to conduct terrorist activities, they will pay for that terrorism through the imposition of billions of dollars in judgments and in penalties,' he said.}}</ref>—and that "hopefully, it's also going to have a deterrent effect, or least cause Iran to think twice about supporting terrorist activity going forward."<ref name="AP: 20 April">{{cite news|last1=Sherman|first1=Mark|title=High Court sides with families of '83 Beirut bombing victims|url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/476d0bf0c83c4c809d86c9c9e393c6f5/terror-victims-win-supreme-court-judgment-against-iran|accessdate=19 June 2016|work=Associated Press|agency=Associated Press|date=April 20, 2016}}</ref> The decision was also praised by [[United States Senator|Senator]] [[Bob Menendez]], who authored §&nbsp;8772, and [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[Paul Ryan]].<ref name="Reuters: 20 April">{{cite news|last1=Hurley|first1=Lawrence|title=U.S. top court rules Iran bank must pay 1983 bomb victims|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-court-iran-idUSKCN0XH1R6|accessdate=19 June 2016|work=Reuters|date=April 20, 2016|quote=Democratic U.S. Senator Bob Menendez of New Jersey, who authored the 2012 legislation in question, called the ruling 'a long-awaited victory for justice.'}}</ref><ref name="AP: 20 April"/>
===Iranian reactions=== A spokesman for [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Iran)|Iran's Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] condemned the ruling as "theft", "incompatible with international law", "a ridicule of justice and law" and stated that Iran "totally reject[s]" the ruling.<ref name="Reuters: decision reaction">{{cite news|last1=Hafezi|first1=Parisa|last2=Balmforth|first2=Richard|title=Iran denounces U.S. ruling awarding Iran money to bomb victims: TV|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-court-iran-reaction-idUSKCN0XI214|accessdate=26 April 2016|work=[[Reuters]]|date=April 21, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Iran calls US Supreme Court ruling on Beirut blast a 'theft'|url=http://english.alarabiya.net/en/News/middle-east/2016/04/21/Iran-calls-US-Supreme-Court-ruling-on-Beirut-blast-a-theft-.html|accessdate=26 April 2016|work=Al Arabiya|agency=Associated Press|date=April 21, 2016}}</ref> The Iranian Foreign Ministry summoned the Swiss ambassador to Iran, who represents U.S. interests in Iran, to receive [[diplomatic note]]s, to be forwarded to the US, protesting the ruling.<ref>{{cite news|title=Iran summons Swiss envoy over US Supreme Court ruling|url=http://theiranproject.com/blog/2016/04/26/iran-summons-swiss-envoy-us-supreme-court-ruling/|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=The Iran Project|agency=[[Mehr News Agency]]|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> A week after the decision was announced, Iranian Foreign Minister [[Mohammad Javad Zarif]] wrote a letter to [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] [[Ban Ki-moon]] urging him to use his [[:wiktionary:good offices|good offices]] to intervene in securing the release of frozen funds and to stop interfering with Iran's international financial transactions.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Nichols|first1=Michelle|last2=Charbonneau|first2=Louis|last3=Hafezi|first3=Parisa|title=Iran asks U.N. chief to intervene with U.S. after court ruling|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-iran-un-idUSKCN0XP32M|accessdate=3 May 2016|work=Reuters|date=April 29, 2016}}</ref><ref name="NYT: April 29">{{cite news|last1=Gladstone|first1=Rick|title=U.S. Rejects Iran's Protest on Asset Ruling|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/30/world/middleeast/us-rejects-irans-protest-on-asset-ruling.html|accessdate=3 May 2016|work=The New York Times|date=April 29, 2016}}</ref> A U.S. State Department spokesman rejected Iran's claims, stating that the State Department "believe[s] the U.S. laws and the application of those laws by the courts of the United States comport with international law."<ref name="NYT: April 29"/>
Iran announced that they would file suit against the United States in the [[International Court of Justice]] (ICJ) for reparations if the U.S. courts begin to "plunder"<!-- <ref name="NYT: ICJ action threatened"/> --> assets from the Citibank account to give to the winning plaintiffs.<ref name="NYT: ICJ action threatened"/> However, the ICJ may not be able to hear the case. The U.S. withdrew its general recognition of the ICJ's jurisdiction in response to the ICJ's ruling in ''[[Nicaragua v. United States]]'', but a 1955 friendship treaty between Iran and the U.S. gives the ICJ jurisdiction to rule on disputes arising from provisions of the treaty.<ref name="NYT: ICJ action threatened">{{cite news|last1=Gladstone|first1=Rick|title=Iran Threatens Lawsuit in Hague Court Over U.S. Ruling on $2 Billion|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/26/world/middleeast/iran-threatens-lawsuit-in-hague-court-over-us-ruling-on-2-billion.html?_r=0|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=April 25, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=No. 4132: Treaty of Amity, Economic Relations, and Consular Rights between the United States of America and Iran, Signed at Tehran, on 15 August 1955.|journal=[[United Nations Treaty Series]]|date=1958|volume=284|page=93|url=https://treaties.un.org/doc/Publication/UNTS/Volume%20284/v284.pdf|accessdate=27 April 2016|format=PDF|via=United Nations Treaty Collection|quote=Any dispute between the High Contracting Parties as to the interpretation or application of the present Treaty, not satisfactorily adjusted by diplomacy, shall be submitted to the International Court of Justice, unless the High Contracting Parties agree to settlement by some other pacific means.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924234226/https://treaties.un.org/doc/Publication/UNTS/Volume%20284/v284.pdf|archive-date=September 24, 2015|deadurl=no}}</ref> A working group has been established in the [[Cabinet of Iran|Iranian Cabinet]] to investigate the ruling and determine ways of reestablishing Iran's rights to the account.<ref name="PressTV: Cabinet working group">{{cite news|title=Iran sets up committee to follow up on US court ruling|url=http://www.presstv.com/Detail/2016/04/26/462695/Iran-US-Supreme-Court-Cabinet-Velayati-Ali-TayyebNiya/|accessdate=28 April 2016|work=[[Press TV]]|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref>
Less than a month after the Supreme Court decision, Iran's parliament overwhelmingly approved—181 votes for, 6 votes against, 8 abstentions—an "emergency bill"<ref name="AM: Iran retaliation bill"/> requiring the government to seek compensation from the U.S. for actions the U.S. has taken against Iran, including the [[1953 Iranian coup d'état]], which the U.S. [[1953 Iranian coup d'état#United States role|helped restore]] the monarch; the [[Nojeh coup plot]]<!-- source and Wikipedia article do not explain how U.S. was involved in this --> in 1980; [[United States support for Iraq during the Iran–Iraq war]], including compensation for over 800,000 Iranians who died or were injured during the conflict; U.S. [[espionage]] in Iran; U.S. [[Israel–United States relations|support]] of [[Israel]]; the alleged death of 17,000 Iranians at the hands of U.S.-supported terrorist groups; and the confiscation of Iranian assets.<ref name="AM: Iran retaliation bill">{{cite news|last1=Karami|first1=Arash|title=Iran Parliament Seeks Damages for US Support of Saddam|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2016/05/iran-parliament-seize-us-assets-coup-iraq-war.html#|accessdate=May 21, 2016|work=Al-Monitor|date=May 16, 2016}}</ref> The bill requires the government to take "appropriate legal action"<!-- <ref name="AM: Iran retaliation bill"/> --> for the violation of Iranian state immunity, including the pursuit of U.S. assets in third countries, and to provide regular updates to parliament on its actions against the US.<ref name="AM: Iran retaliation bill"/>
Some Iranian officials, including the chief of the Central Bank of Iran (CBI), have placed some blame for the Citibank account's seizure on [[Government of Mahmoud Ahmadinejad (2005–13)|the previous administration]] of [[Mahmoud Ahmadinejad]],<ref name="FT: Blame on Ahmadinejad"/><ref name="TIP: April 24 headlines">{{cite news|title=A look at Iranian newspaper front pages on Apr. 24|url=http://theiranproject.com/blog/2016/04/24/look-iranian-newspaper-front-pages-apr-24/|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=The Iran Project|issue=April 24, 2016}}</ref> who was president of Iran from 2005 to 2013.<ref>{{cite web|title=Mahmoud Ahmadinejad Fast Facts|url=http://www.cnn.com/2012/12/10/world/meast/mahmoud-ahmadinejad---fast-facts/|website=CNN|accessdate=3 May 2016|quote=August 3, 2005 – Sworn in as president&nbsp;... August 4, 2013 – Rouhani is sworn in and Ahmadinejad officially leaves office.}}</ref><ref name="AM: Ahmadinejad blame">{{cite news|last1=Karami|first1=Arash|title=Who's to blame for US seizure of $2 billion in Iranian assets?|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2016/04/ahmadinejad-us-supreme-court-iran-terror-2-billion.html#|accessdate=3 May 2016|work=[[Al-Monitor]]|date=April 28, 2016}}</ref> The Foreign Ministry's director for political and security affairs, Hamid Baidinejad, said it was "reckless"<!-- <ref name="FT: Blame on Ahmadinejad"/> --> for the previous administration to have invested in U.S. securities.<ref name="FT: Blame on Ahmadinejad"/> In a post on the CBI's website, its chief pointed out that: "Although CBI experts and senior officials had warned against investing in dollar denominated securities, the government of president Mahmoud Ahmadinejad went ahead and purchased it, thus paving the way for the damage done to our assets."<ref name="FT: Blame on Ahmadinejad">{{cite news|title=Negligence of Former Gov't Imposed Heavy Costs|url=http://financialtribune.com/articles/economy-business-and-markets/40167/negligence-former-gov%E2%80%99t-imposed-heavy-costs|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=Financial Tribune|date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> [[Hamid Baeidinejad]], a senior Foreign Ministry official, criticized the former head of the CBI for investing in a "hostile country".<ref name="AM: Ahmadinejad blame"/><!-- See also: <ref name="TIP: April 26 headlines">{{cite news|title=A Look at Iranian Newspaper Front Pages on Apr. 26|url=http://theiranproject.com/blog/2016/04/26/look-iranian-newspaper-front-pages-apr-26/|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=The Iran Project|date=April 26, 2016|quote=Ahmadinejad Gov't Officials Should Be Prosecuted for Investing in Hostile Country: Advisor}}</ref> -->
===Impact on US-Iran relations=== The decision came at a delicate time for relations between Iran and Western nations, which were removing sanctions on Iran after its compliance with [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|an agreement]] for curtailing development of [[Nuclear program of Iran|its nuclear enrichment program]].<ref name="Reuters: decision reaction"/><ref name="NYT: ICJ action threatened"/><ref name="PressTV: Cabinet working group"/><ref name="TIP: Gov officials reactions">{{cite news|title=Iran top officials dismiss U.S. court ruling as 'international robbery'|url=http://theiranproject.com/blog/2016/04/26/iran-top-officials-dismiss-us-court-ruling-as-international-robbery/|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=The Iran Project|date=April 26, 2016}}</ref> The agreement stipulated that once Iranian compliance with the terms of the agreement was verified, most [[sanctions against Iran]] would be lifted, including all sanctions imposed by the [[United Nations Security Council]] as well as nuclear-related [[European Union]] and U.S. sanctions; U.S. sanctions against Iran for terrorism, human rights abuses, and ballistic missiles would not be affected.<ref>{{cite press release |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |title=Parameters for a Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action Regarding the Islamic Republic of Iran's Nuclear Program |url=https://www.state.gov/r/pa/prs/ps/2015/04/240170.htm |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Office of the Spokesperson, U.S. Department of State |date=April 2, 2015 |access-date=2016-04-27}}</ref> In mid-January 2016, most sanctions were lifted.<ref name="AP: Sanctions lifted">{{cite news|last1=Jahn|first1=George|last2=Klapper|first2=Bradley|title=US, EU lift sanctions against Iran amid landmark nuke deal|url=http://www.bigstory.ap.org/article/f904aca375294a3b952f47458437f692/iranian-us-foreign-minister-focus-clinching-nuclear-deal|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=Associated Press|date=January 16, 2016}}</ref><ref name="WP: sanctions lifted">{{cite news|last1=Murphy|first1=Brian|title=Iran claims $100 billion now freed in major step as sanctions roll back|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/iran-claims-100-billion-now-freed-in-major-step-as-sanctions-roll-back/2016/02/01/edfc23ca-c8e5-11e5-a7b2-5a2f824b02c9_story.html|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=Washington Post|date=February 1, 2016}}</ref> In March, the District Court for the Southern District of New York found, by default, that Iran had provided support to certain terrorist groups and individuals responsible for the [[September 11 attacks]] and awarded $10.5&nbsp;billion in damages to the plaintiffs, which consisted of $3&nbsp;billion to reimburse insurance companies for paid claims and $7.5&nbsp;billion for victims and their families ($2&nbsp;million for [[pain and suffering]] and $6.88&nbsp;million in punitive damages per victim).<ref>{{cite news|last1=van Voris|first1=Bob|title=Iran Told to Pay $10.5 Billion to Sept. 11 Kin, Insurers|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-10/iran-told-to-pay-10-5-billion-to-sept-11-kin-insurers|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=Bloomberg|date=March 9, 2016}}</ref> The same judge ruled just six months earlier that there was insufficient evidence linking [[Saudi Arabia]]—which has sour relations with Iran—to the 9/11 attacks to overcome, under the terrorism exemption, Saudi Arabia's immunity under the FSIA.<ref name="AM: Impact on US foreign policy"/><ref name="The Hill: Saudi 9-11 case dismissed">{{cite news|last1=Hattem|first1=Julia|title=Judge dismisses 9/11 charges against Saudi Arabia|url=http://thehill.com/policy/national-security/255419-judge-dismisses-9-11-charges-against-saudi-arabia|accessdate=21 May 2016|work=The Hill|date=September 30, 2015}}</ref>
[[File:Secretary Kerry Addresses Reporters Before Meeting With Iranian Foreign Minister Zarif (25979802543).jpg|thumb|[[Secretary of State]] [[John Kerry]] meeting with Iranian Foreign Minister Mohammad Javad Zarif two days after the Supreme Court's decision was released]] The Supreme Court's decision was announced while Iran's Foreign Minister, Mohammad Javad Zarif, was visiting the United States.<ref>{{cite press release |author=John Kerry |title=Remarks After Meeting Iranian Foreign Minister Zarif |url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2016/04/255977.htm |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Office of the Spokesperson, U.S. Department of State |date=April 19, 2016 |access-date=2016-04-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |author=John Kerry |title=Remarks Before Meeting with Iranian Foreign Minister Javad Zarif |url=https://www.state.gov/secretary/remarks/2016/04/256536.htm |location=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Office of the Spokesperson, U.S. Department of State |date=April 22, 2016 |access-date=2016-04-27}}</ref> The week before the decision was announced, the head of the Central Bank of Iran had visited Washington, during the spring meetings of the [[World Bank]] and [[International Monetary Fund]], to discuss with U.S. and foreign officials problems that remained with Iranian access to international banking, despite the lifting of sanctions.<ref name="WSJ: Saif visits Washington">{{cite news|last1=Solomon|first1=Jay|last2=Fitch|first2=Asa|last3=Faucon|first3=Benoit|title=Iran's Central Bank Chief Warns Banking-Access Issues Jeopardize Nuclear Deal|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/irans-central-bank-chief-warns-banking-access-issues-jeopardize-nuclear-deal-1460745930|accessdate=28 April 2016|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lange|first1=Jason|title=Iran calls on U.S., EU to help it access global financial system|url=http://news.trust.org/item/20160415144625-6gm0j|accessdate=28 April 2016|work=Thompson Reuters Foundation News|agency=Reuters|date=April 15, 2016}}</ref> Javad Zarif criticized the ''Bank Markazi'' decision and the "even more absurd" 9/11 decision by the New York as "the height of absurdity".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wright|first1=Robin|title=Iran's Javad Zarif on the Fraying Nuclear Deal, U.S. Relations, and Holocaust Cartoons|url=http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/irans-javad-zarif-on-the-fraying-nuclear-deal-u-s-relations-and-holocaust-cartoons|accessdate=28 April 2016|work=The New Yorker|date=April 25, 2016}}</ref> [[President of Iran|Iranian President]] [[Hassan Rouhani]] called the decisions "open hostility by the United States against the Iranian people."<ref name="AFP: Khamenei remarks">{{cite news|title=Iran's Khamenei says US lifted sanctions only on paper|url=http://www.dailymagazine.news/iran-s-khamenei-says-us-lifted-sanctions-only-on-paper-nid-145890.html|accessdate=27 April 2016|work=Daily Magazine|agency=[[Agence France-Presse|AFP]]|date=April 27, 2016}}</ref>
Under the nuclear agreement, an important policy objective was to ensure that the Iranian economy benefits from suspending its nuclear weapons program.<ref name="AM: Impact on US foreign policy">{{cite news|last1=Borhani|first1=Saam|title=How Supreme Court decision to freeze Iran assets undermines US foreign policy|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2016/05/us-supreme-court-iranian-asset-seizures-terror-victims.html|accessdate=21 May 2016|work=Al-Monitor|date=May 17, 2016}}</ref> In the view of commentators Ali Omidi, a professor of [[international relations]] at the [[University of Isfahan]], and Saam Borhani, an attorney and commentator on US-Iran relations and sanctions law, the ''Bank Markazi'' decision and the 9/11 case threaten to undermine the nuclear deal and American credibility in negotiations with Iran.<ref name="AM: Impact on US foreign policy"/><ref name="AM: 4 ways decision undermines relations">{{cite news|last1=Omidi|first1=Ali|title=Four ways US seizure of Iranian assets will impact bilateral ties|url=http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2016/05/us-supreme-court-2-billion-iranian-assets-seizure.html|accessdate=21 May 2016|work=Al-Monitor|date=May 13, 2016}}</ref> The head of the Nuclear Committee in Iran's parliament, Ibrahim Karkhaneh, decried the rulings as "cooperation between the American Congress, the government and courts to steal Iranian property."<ref name="AM: Iran retaliation bill"/>
