'''Karin P. Huffer''' was an American [[Family therapy|marriage and family therapist]], who is known for identifying a potential consequence of [[legal abuse]], the condition known as Legal Abuse Syndrome (LAS), a form of [[Post-traumatic Stress Disorder|post traumatic stress disorder (PTSD)]] which can be caused by ethical violation, [[betrayal]], [[abuse of power]], lack of [[accountability]], or fraud within the legal system.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Holding|first1=Reynolds|title=HOLDING COURT — A Sick and Twisted System|url=http://www.tulanelink.com/tulanelink/legalabuse_box.htm|publisher=San Francisco Chronicle}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Shemeligian|first1=Bob|title=Courtrooms guilty of stress disorder|url=http://lasvegassun.com/news/1996/jul/22/courtrooms-guilty-of-stress-disorder/|website=http://lasvegassun.com/|publisher=Las Vegas Sun|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Dr. Karin Huffer|url=https://casetext.com/users/dr-karin-huffer|website=casetext.com|publisher=Case Text|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>
==Background== Since 1988, Huffer has worked to develop methods in training advocates in court to help those suffering from LAS. A diagnosis of LAS-related PTSD directs the court, through the [[Americans With Disabilities Act]], to offer special accommodations to the litigant. As one of the few recognized expert witnesses in the field of LAS, Dr. Huffer provides treatment, consultation, and expert witness testimony for persons with disabilities, including invisible disabilities, (i.e. autism, [[Traumatic brain injury|TBI]], PTSD, depression, and anxiety) across the country.<ref>{{cite web|title=Court can be life-changing|url=https://www.newsreview.com/reno/court-can-be-life-changing/content?oid=15103429|website=NewsReview.com|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>
==Current work== Huffer trains advocates working with clients effected by the Americans with Disabilities Act in methods to provide accommodations for legal abuse-related symptoms through a program called Equal Access Advocates.<ref>{{cite web|title=EAA Advocate Training: About Us|url=http://www.equalaccessadvocates.com/about-us/|website=Equal Access Advocates|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref> Huffer has been an Associate Professor in Counseling and Forensic Psychology at Kings International University and is currently working as an Adjunct Professor at [[John Jay College]], a part of the [[City University of New York]], in the College of Criminal Justice.<ref name="King's International University, Forensic Psychology, Faculty Member">{{cite web|title=Karin P. Huffer, King's International University, Forensic Psychology, Faculty Member|url=https://lvaallc.academia.edu/KarinHuffer|website=academia.edu|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=About Dr. Karin Huffer|url=https://casetext.com/users/dr-karin-huffer|website=CaseText.com|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref> She is the author of several books and is an accomplished speaker on the subject of Legal Abuse Syndrome.<ref>{{cite web|title=Overcoming the Devastation of Legal Abuse Syndrome|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0964178605|website=amazon.com|}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Unlocking Justice|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/B00HYKWB2Y|website=amazon.com|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Legal Abuse Syndrome: 8 Steps for Avoiding the Traumatic Stress Caused by the Justice System|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/1481744682|website=amazon.com|}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=International Conference The Rule of Law in an Era of Change: Security, Social Justice and Inclusive Governance|url=http://johnjay.jjay.cuny.edu/ic_greece/InternationalProgramGreece.pdf|website=John Jay CUNY EDU|publisher=John Jay College, City University of New York}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=UCLA School of Law Panels: Legal Remedies for People with Disabilities|url=http://escholarship.org/uc/item/5nq856fn|website=UCLA School of Law|publisher=UCLA|accessdate=30 December 2015}}</ref>
